f:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"GMX calculates funding rates every hour based on the difference between perpetual and oracle prices, sourced from Chainlink price feeds. The funding payment occurs between long and short positions directly through the protocol, with rates determined by position imbalances in the GLP/GM liquidity pools. Unlike CEX funding, GMX's oracle dependency means funding rates can diverge significantly from spot market conditions, especially during high volatility periods."}]
10:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","WIF","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"WIF's meme token status creates extreme funding rate volatility on GMX, often exceeding traditional assets by 3-5x during trending periods. The token's correlation with Solana ecosystem movements and retail sentiment makes it particularly sensitive to position imbalances, generating frequent arbitrage opportunities between GMX and centralized exchanges."}]]}]
11:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"WIF funding rates on GMX have shown extreme volatility, ranging from -2% to +4% during major price movements in Q4 2023. The 1-hour interval structure means rates can compound quickly, with sustained periods of high funding often lasting 6-12 hours during viral social media events. Peak funding periods typically coincide with Solana network activity spikes and broader meme coin rotation cycles. The oracle-based pricing system has created notable disconnects during flash crashes, with funding rates persisting at extreme levels while spot prices recover."}]]}]
12:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between GMX and Binance/OKX frequently emerges when WIF funding rates diverge by more than 0.5% annually. The most profitable setups occur when GMX funding exceeds CEX rates during retail FOMO periods, allowing traders to short on GMX while longing on centralized venues. Gas costs on Arbitrum (typically $0.50-2.00 per transaction) remain manageable for position sizes above $10,000. Risk management requires monitoring Chainlink oracle updates and GLP utilization rates, as extreme pool imbalances can lead to sudden funding reversals."}]]}]
13:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Oracle dependency presents the primary risk, as Chainlink feed delays during extreme volatility can create temporary mispricing scenarios lasting 5-15 minutes. Price impact becomes significant above $100,000 position sizes due to GLP pool depth limitations, especially during low-liquidity Asian trading hours. Counter-party risk differs from CEX exposure as positions are settled against smart contracts, but potential GM pool insolvency during extreme market stress remains theoretical. Funding rate reversals can occur rapidly when whale positions close, making position monitoring and tight stop-losses essential for consistent profitability."}]]}]
14:["$","$L16",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often do WIF funding rates update on GMX?","answer":"WIF funding rates update every hour on GMX, calculated based on the difference between perpetual price and Chainlink oracle feeds. This 1-hour interval allows for more frequent arbitrage opportunities compared to 8-hour CEX funding cycles."},{"question":"What's the maximum position size for WIF on GMX?","answer":"Maximum WIF position size depends on GLP pool utilization, typically capped around $500,000-1M per side. Large positions face increasing price impact and borrowing fees as they approach pool limits."},{"question":"How does GMX funding compare to centralized exchanges?","answer":"GMX funding rates often diverge significantly from CEX rates due to oracle-based pricing and different user bases. WIF funding on GMX tends to be more volatile and can persist at extreme levels longer than Binance or OKX."},{"question":"What are the main costs for WIF arbitrage on GMX?","answer":"Primary costs include 0.05%-0.07% trading fees, Arbitrum gas fees ($0.50-2.00), and potential price impact on larger sizes. Borrowing fees may apply for positions exceeding pool capacity limits during high utilization periods."}]}]
